@page "/get-involved"

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HERO (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="hero">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h1>Get Involved</h1>
        <p>
            Ripple is presented as a community‑driven initiative within a college honors project. 
            While there is no active facility or volunteer program, this page models how people 
            could engage with a real aquaponics‑based nonprofit through learning, collaboration, 
            and community participation.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- WAYS TO GET INVOLVED (pale coral) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Ways to Get Involved (Conceptual)</h2>

        <div class="gi-grid">

            <div class="gi-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-hand-holding-heart gi-icon"></i>
                <h3>Volunteer with Ripple</h3>
                <p>
                    In this conceptual model, volunteers would help with planting, harvesting, 
                    packaging, cleaning, and outreach. These roles illustrate how community members 
                    might participate in a real aquaponics program.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="gi-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-seedling gi-icon"></i>
                <h3>Community Garden & Personal Systems</h3>
                <p>
                    The project includes examples of small‑scale aquaponic units for personal or 
                    community garden use. These systems demonstrate how families, students, and 
                    hobbyists could learn aquaponics hands‑on.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="gi-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-chalkboard-user gi-icon"></i>
                <h3>Workshops & Tours</h3>
                <p>
                    Workshops and tours are described as part of the educational model. While not 
                    offered in reality, they represent how a real nonprofit could teach aquaponics, 
                    sustainability, and food system design.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="gi-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-flask gi-icon"></i>
                <h3>Research & Collaboration</h3>
                <p>
                    Students, educators, and researchers are imagined as partners in studying system 
                    design, sustainability, biology, and community impact. These collaborations are 
                    conceptual and included to show how academic engagement could work.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="gi-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-heart gi-icon"></i>
                <h3>Support Our Work</h3>
                <p>
                    Support in this project is hypothetical. The site outlines donations, partnerships, 
                    and community engagement to demonstrate how a real nonprofit might sustain its work.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- CTA SECTION (pale blue) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner gi-cta">
        <h2>Ready to Get Involved?</h2>
        <p>
            Since Ripple is a proof‑of‑concept project, there are no real volunteer shifts or 
            collaboration programs. However, this page illustrates how community members could 
            connect with a real aquaponics nonprofit if the model were implemented.
        </p>

        <div class="gi-buttons">
            <a href="/donate" class="btn donate-btn">Donate (Demo)</a>
            <a href="/contact" class="btn primary">Contact Us</a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
